Raw dev notes -- RAG Pipeline: Getting Data In (and Not Losing My Mind)

Okay, so this past week has been a deep dive into getting my RAG knowledge base pipeline actually *fed* with content. The whole idea behind this project is to build a robust system that can ingest content from various sources, process it, and make it available for a Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) system. Basically, I want to feed an LLM with my own structured knowledge so it can give better, more accurate answers based on my specific content.

What I actually did this week was pretty foundational, but also pretty gnarly. The big win was getting the incremental content updater working. This thing pulls content from a WordPress site via its REST API, converts the HTML into clean Markdown, and then, crucially, only updates what's changed. This is a huge step because it means I don't have to re-process everything every time. I also got the initial project structure and documentation laid out in a `CLAUDE.md` file, which is my go-to for project setup and conventions. It's boring but essential for keeping my future self sane. There was also a small commit to add a Hebrew name to an author section in the WordPress-to-RAG pipeline showcase, which was a nice personal touch.

The hardest part, by far, was the HTML-to-Markdown conversion and making the incremental updates truly robust. HTML is a wild west of tags, classes, and inline styles, and trying to consistently convert that into clean, semantic Markdown without losing important information (or introducing weird artifacts) is a constant battle. I swear, every time I think I've handled all the edge cases, a new one pops up. And then there's the "incremental" part – figuring out what's actually changed, what's new, and what's been deleted, without hammering the API or doing unnecessary work. It's a delicate dance of timestamps and content hashes. I definitely spent more time than I'd like to admit staring at diffs and trying to debug why a seemingly identical piece of content was being re-processed. The WordPress REST API itself also has its quirks, like pagination and sometimes inconsistent data structures, which always adds an extra layer of "fun."

Honestly, it felt good to get this core data ingestion piece working. It's not the flashy LLM part, but it's the plumbing that makes everything else possible. There's a real satisfaction in seeing data flow cleanly from one system to another, transformed and ready for its next stage. It's a reminder that even the most advanced AI systems are only as good as the data you feed them, and getting that data right is a significant engineering challenge in itself. I'm learning so much about robust data pipelines and text processing, which feels like a really valuable skill to hone. It's all about building reliable foundations.

Next up: Chunking and embedding the processed Markdown content.
